ridgeprovides\", \"from\": 324, \"to\": 341}, {\"ngram\": \"a member\", \"from\": 353, \"to\": 361}]}, {\"sentence\": \"View all partners https://doi.org/10.64628/AB.eruccemwp Share article Print article Paris's Olympic opening ceremony on July 26 was the cause of much online discussion.\", \"from\": 387, \"to\": 559, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"all partners https://doi.org/10.64628/AB.eruccemwp\", \"from\": 392, \"to\": 442}, {\"ngram\": \"Share article Print article Paris's Olympic opening ceremony\", \"from\": 443, \"to\": 503}, {\"ngram\": \"July\", \"from\": 507, \"to\": 511}, {\"ngram\": \"the cause\", \"from\": 519, \"to\": 528}, {\"ngram\": \"much online discussion\", \"from\": 532, \"to\": 554}]}, {\"sentence\": \"No moment more so, perhaps, than whenseveral drag queenswere shown seated at a long table.\", \"from\": 560, \"to\": 650, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"No moment\", \"from\": 560, \"to\": 569}, {\"ngram\": \"whenseveral drag\", \"from\": 593, \"to\": 609}, {\"ngram\": \"a long table\", \"from\": 637, \"to\": 649}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Many viewers, includingPope FrancisandAyatollah Khamanei, interpreted the scene as a parody mocking Leonardo da Vinci's painting The Last Supper (c. 1495).\", \"from\": 652, \"to\": 807, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 752, \"end\": 769, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leonardo_da_Vinci\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.408395747458522e-36, \"text\": \"Leonardo da Vinci\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leonardo_da_Vinci\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leonardo_da_Vinci\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Many viewers\", \"from\": 652, \"to\": 664}, {\"ngram\": \"includingPope FrancisandAyatollah Khamanei\", \"from\": 666, \"to\": 708}, {\"ngram\": \"the scene\", \"from\": 722, \"to\": 731}, {\"ngram\": \"a parody\", \"from\": 735, \"to\": 743}, {\"ngram\": \"The Last Supper\", \"from\": 781, \"to\": 796}, {\"ngram\": \"c.\", \"from\": 798, \"to\": 800}]}, {\"sentence\": \"By extension, they claimed that the opening ceremony mocked the Last Supper, the event Christians believe instituted the Eucharist celebration - and Christianity itself.\", \"from\": 808, \"to\": 977, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 895, \"end\": 905, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999999826954992, \"rank\": 1.730448677528004e-08, \"text\": \"Christians\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 929, \"end\": 950, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eucharist_in_the_Catholic_Church\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Eucharist celebration\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eucharist_in_the_Catholic_Church\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Eucharist_in_the_Catholic_Church\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"extension\", \"from\": 811, \"to\": 820}, {\"ngram\": \"the opening ceremony\", \"from\": 840, \"to\": 860}, {\"ngram\": \"the Last Supper\", \"from\": 868, \"to\": 883}, {\"ngram\": \"the event\", \"from\": 885, \"to\": 894}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The outrage has been so intense in some quarters that the ceremony organisers have beensubject to death threats.\", \"from\": 978, \"to\": 1090, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The outrage\", \"from\": 978, \"to\": 989}, {\"ngram\": \"some quarters\", \"from\": 1013, \"to\": 1026}, {\"ngram\": \"the ceremony organisers\", \"from\": 1032, \"to\": 1055}, {\"ngram\": \"death threats\", \"from\": 1076, \"to\": 1089}]}, {\"sentence\": \"I believe these responses fundamentally misinterpret the scene, which was not supposed to reference the Last Supper at all.\", \"from\": 1092, \"to\": 1215, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"these responses\", \"from\": 1102, \"to\": 1117}, {\"ngram\": \"the scene\", \"from\": 1145, \"to\": 1154}, {\"ngram\": \"the Last Supper\", \"from\": 1192, \"to\": 1207}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The director of the ceremony, Thomas Jolly, wasprincipally inspirednot by da Vinci'sThe Last Supper, but byLe Festin Des Dieux(The Feast of God, c. 1635-1640) a painting by Jan van Bijlert.\", \"from\": 1216, \"to\": 1405, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1246, \"end\": 1252, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Thomas_the_Apostle\", \"score\": 0.9999999999990905, \"rank\": 7.036020222852023e-13, \"text\": \"Thomas\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q43115\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Thomas_the_Apostle\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Thomas_the_Apostle\"}, {\"begin\": 1389, \"end\": 1404, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jan_van_Bijlert\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Jan van Bijlert\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q483501\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jan_van_Bijlert\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jan_van_Bijlert\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The director\", \"from\": 1216, \"to\": 1228}, {\"ngram\": \"the ceremony\", \"from\": 1232, \"to\": 1244}, {\"ngram\": \"da Vinci'sThe Last Supper\", \"from\": 1290, \"to\": 1315}, {\"ngram\": \"byLe Festin Des Dieux(The Feast\", \"from\": 1321, \"to\": 1352}, {\"ngram\": \"God\", \"from\": 1356, \"to\": 1359}, {\"ngram\": \"a painting\", \"from\": 1375, \"to\": 1385}]}, {\"sentence\": \"This painting depicts the marriage of the characters from ancient Greek mythology, Thetis and Peleus, with the god Dionysus and his satyrs dancing in the foreground.\", \"from\": 1407, \"to\": 1572, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1465, \"end\": 1478, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greek_religion\", \"score\": 0.9999999924639269, \"rank\": 7.534252969487591e-09, \"text\": \"ancient Greek\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greek_religion\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greek_religion\"}, {\"begin\": 1473, \"end\": 1488, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.0053613917017962e-27, \"text\": \"Greek mythology\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\"}, {\"begin\": 1522, \"end\": 1530, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"This painting\", \"from\": 1407, \"to\": 1420}, {\"ngram\": \"the marriage\", \"from\": 1429, \"to\": 1441}, {\"ngram\": \"the characters\", \"from\": 1445, \"to\": 1459}, {\"ngram\": \"Thetis\", \"from\": 1490, \"to\": 1496}, {\"ngram\": \"Peleus\", \"from\": 1501, \"to\": 1507}, {\"ngram\": \"his satyrs\", \"from\": 1535, \"to\": 1545}, {\"ngram\": \"the foreground\", \"from\": 1557, \"to\": 1571}]}, {\"sentence\": \"This makes considerably more sense considering Le Festin is housed at the Mus\\u00e9e Magninin in Dijon, France.\", \"from\": 1573, \"to\": 1679, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1665, \"end\": 1670, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dijon\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 5.827005404172661e-15, \"text\": \"Dijon\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dijon\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dijon\"}, {\"begin\": 1672, \"end\": 1678, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"score\": 0.7069675842133759, \"rank\": 0.4143421799656391, \"text\": \"France\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"considerably more sense\", \"from\": 1584, \"to\": 1607}, {\"ngram\": \"Le Festin\", \"from\": 1620, \"to\": 1629}, {\"ngram\": \"the Mus\\u00e9e Magninin\", \"from\": 1643, \"to\": 1661}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The Last Supper, meanwhile, resides in Milan (quite ironically, as Milan will be the site of the 2026 Winter Olympics).\", \"from\": 1680, \"to\": 1799, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1719, \"end\": 1724, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Milan\", \"score\": 0.9999999986234798, \"rank\": 1.3760617868494802e-09, \"text\": \"Milan\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Milan\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Milan\"}, {\"begin\": 1747, \"end\": 1752, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Milan\", \"score\": 0.9999999986234798, \"rank\": 1.3760617868494802e-09, \"text\": \"Milan\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Milan\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Milan\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The Last Supper\", \"from\": 1680, \"to\": 1695}, {\"ngram\": \"the site\", \"from\": 1761, \"to\": 1769}, {\"ngram\": \"the 2026 Winter Olympics\", \"from\": 1773, \"to\": 1797}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The confusion between these two scenes is not merely a product of the internet's rage cycle.\", \"from\": 1803, \"to\": 1895, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The confusion\", \"from\": 1803, \"to\": 1816}, {\"ngram\": \"these two scenes\", \"from\": 1825, \"to\": 1841}, {\"ngram\": \"a product\", \"from\": 1856, \"to\": 1865}, {\"ngram\": \"the internet's rage cycle\", \"from\": 1869, \"to\": 1894}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Asmany commentators have noted, much of the confusion is grounded in the failure of Christian audiences (and others) to recognise the debt Christian iconography owes topre-Christian Greco-Roman imagery.\", \"from\": 1896, \"to\": 2098, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1980, \"end\": 1989, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999999977158041, \"rank\": 2.2840807942604358e-09, \"text\": \"Christian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 2035, \"end\": 2056, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iconography\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Christian iconography\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iconography\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Iconography\"}, {\"begin\": 2078, \"end\": 2089, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"score\": 0.9999999883048077, \"rank\": 1.169455312396202e-08, \"text\": \"Greco-Roman\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Asmany commentators\", \"from\": 1896, \"to\": 1915}, {\"ngram\": \"the confusion\", \"from\": 1936, \"to\": 1949}, {\"ngram\": \"the failure\", \"from\": 1965, \"to\": 1976}, {\"ngram\": \"others\", \"from\": 2005, \"to\": 2011}, {\"ngram\": \"the debt\", \"from\": 2026, \"to\": 2034}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But more than this, a failure to recognise the long standing connection that many historians see between Jesus and Dionysus.\", \"from\": 2099, \"to\": 2223, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2204, \"end\": 2209, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\", \"score\": 0.9999999976243998, \"rank\": 2.3757717043300036e-09, \"text\": \"Jesus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\"}, {\"begin\": 2214, \"end\": 2222, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the long standing connection\", \"from\": 2142, \"to\": 2170}, {\"ngram\": \"many historians\", \"from\": 2176, \"to\": 2191}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Understanding this connection and its influence on early Christianity is crucial for understanding not only the scene at the Olympics but also, I believe, the broader history of Christianity.\", \"from\": 2225, \"to\": 2416, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2276, \"end\": 2294, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 5.606827794088226e-16, \"text\": \"early Christianity\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 2403, \"end\": 2415, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999998425796672, \"rank\": 1.5742042643154214e-07, \"text\": \"Christianity\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"this connection\", \"from\": 2239, \"to\": 2254}, {\"ngram\": \"its influence\", \"from\": 2259, \"to\": 2272}, {\"ngram\": \"understanding\", \"from\": 2310, \"to\": 2323}, {\"ngram\": \"not only the scene\", \"from\": 2324, \"to\": 2342}, {\"ngram\": \"the Olympics\", \"from\": 2346, \"to\": 2358}, {\"ngram\": \"the broader history\", \"from\": 2380, \"to\": 2399}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Many historians believe thatChristianity as we know it began as a Roman mystery cult- a type of religious expression that emerged out of dissatisfaction with Rome's traditional religious practices.\", \"from\": 2418, \"to\": 2615, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2484, \"end\": 2489, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"score\": 0.9999999929177648, \"rank\": 7.081154080147751e-09, \"text\": \"Roman\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\"}, {\"begin\": 2576, \"end\": 2580, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.9999651660778821, \"rank\": 2.259647884511832e-05, \"text\": \"Rome\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Many historians\", \"from\": 2418, \"to\": 2433}, {\"ngram\": \"thatChristianity\", \"from\": 2442, \"to\": 2458}, {\"ngram\": \"a type\", \"from\": 2504, \"to\": 2510}, {\"ngram\": \"religious expression\", \"from\": 2514, \"to\": 2534}, {\"ngram\": \"dissatisfaction\", \"from\": 2555, \"to\": 2570}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Rome's so-called \\\"civic cults\\\" tended to be based around communal ritual with little spiritual substance for the individual believer.\", \"from\": 2617, \"to\": 2750, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2617, \"end\": 2621, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.9999651660778821, \"rank\": 2.259647884511832e-05, \"text\": \"Rome\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"communal ritual\", \"from\": 2674, \"to\": 2689}, {\"ngram\": \"little spiritual substance\", \"from\": 2695, \"to\": 2721}, {\"ngram\": \"the individual believer\", \"from\": 2726, \"to\": 2749}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\\"Mystery cults\\\" provided spiritual substance and direct access to the divine for individuals.\", \"from\": 2751, \"to\": 2844, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Mystery cults\", \"from\": 2752, \"to\": 2765}, {\"ngram\": \"spiritual substance\", \"from\": 2776, \"to\": 2795}, {\"ngram\": \"direct access\", \"from\": 2800, \"to\": 2813}, {\"ngram\": \"the divine\", \"from\": 2817, \"to\": 2827}, {\"ngram\": \"individuals\", \"from\": 2832, \"to\": 2843}]}, {\"sentence\": \"These mystery religions offered believers a sense of connection with the divine and the hope of eternal life.\", \"from\": 2845, \"to\": 2954, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"These mystery religions\", \"from\": 2845, \"to\": 2868}, {\"ngram\": \"believers\", \"from\": 2877, \"to\": 2886}, {\"ngram\": \"a sense\", \"from\": 2887, \"to\": 2894}, {\"ngram\": \"connection\", \"from\": 2898, \"to\": 2908}, {\"ngram\": \"the hope\", \"from\": 2929, \"to\": 2937}, {\"ngram\": \"eternal life\", \"from\": 2941, \"to\": 2953}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Christianity seemingly adopted the messianic figure of a recently formed Jewish sect for their saviour.Others turned to the Greek god Dionysus, re-imagined in a similar form to that of the Jewish rabbi.\", \"from\": 2955, \"to\": 3157, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2955, \"end\": 2967, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999998425796672, \"rank\": 1.5742042643154214e-07, \"text\": \"Christianity\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 3028, \"end\": 3039, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jewish_Christian\", \"score\": 0.999999988734544, \"rank\": 1.126526298659269e-08, \"text\": \"Jewish sect\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jewish_Christian\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jewish_Christian\"}, {\"begin\": 3079, \"end\": 3084, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"score\": 0.9999999919928086, \"rank\": 8.007415592497854e-09, \"text\": \"Greek\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\"}, {\"begin\": 3089, \"end\": 3097, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}, {\"begin\": 3144, \"end\": 3150, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Judaism\", \"score\": 0.9999999995047801, \"rank\": 4.950219362366931e-10, \"text\": \"Jewish\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Judaism\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Judaism\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the messianic figure\", \"from\": 2986, \"to\": 3006}, {\"ngram\": \"their saviour\", \"from\": 3044, \"to\": 3057}, {\"ngram\": \"Others\", \"from\": 3058, \"to\": 3064}, {\"ngram\": \"a similar form\", \"from\": 3114, \"to\": 3128}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Dionysus is often described as \\\"the god of wine and the theatre\\\".\", \"from\": 3159, \"to\": 3224, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3159, \"end\": 3167, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the god\", \"from\": 3191, \"to\": 3198}, {\"ngram\": \"wine\", \"from\": 3202, \"to\": 3206}, {\"ngram\": \"the theatre\", \"from\": 3211, \"to\": 3222}]}, {\"sentence\": \"He and his Roman counterpart, Bacchus, are associated with debauchery, drunkenness and licentiousness.\", \"from\": 3225, \"to\": 3327, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3236, \"end\": 3241, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"score\": 0.9999999929177648, \"rank\": 7.081154080147751e-09, \"text\": \"Roman\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\"}, {\"begin\": 3255, \"end\": 3262, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ariadne_auf_Naxos\", \"score\": 0.9907540256642337, \"rank\": 0.009331435672861996, \"text\": \"Bacchus\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ariadne_auf_Naxos\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ariadne_auf_Naxos\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"debauchery\", \"from\": 3284, \"to\": 3294}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In later centuries, Christianity adopted an ethic associated with its austere monastic elements, so it's understandable that today the comparison of Christ with Dionysus could offend or shock.\", \"from\": 3328, \"to\": 3520, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3348, \"end\": 3360, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999998425796672, \"rank\": 1.5742042643154214e-07, \"text\": \"Christianity\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 3489, \"end\": 3497, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"later centuries\", \"from\": 3331, \"to\": 3346}, {\"ngram\": \"its austere monastic elements\", \"from\": 3394, \"to\": 3423}, {\"ngram\": \"the comparison\", \"from\": 3459, \"to\": 3473}, {\"ngram\": \"Christ\", \"from\": 3477, \"to\": 3483}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But a look beneath these facile understandings of Dionysus shows a much more complex picture.\", \"from\": 3521, \"to\": 3614, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3571, \"end\": 3579, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"a look\", \"from\": 3525, \"to\": 3531}, {\"ngram\": \"these facile understandings\", \"from\": 3540, \"to\": 3567}, {\"ngram\": \"a much more complex picture\", \"from\": 3586, \"to\": 3613}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Dionysus was not just a deity associated with wine, but can also be interpreted as a god of the enlightenment that comes from placing yourself in liminal spaces, that is to say the places on the margins of society and, importantly, of nature.\", \"from\": 3616, \"to\": 3858, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3616, \"end\": 3624, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"just a deity\", \"from\": 3633, \"to\": 3645}, {\"ngram\": \"wine\", \"from\": 3662, \"to\": 3666}, {\"ngram\": \"a god\", \"from\": 3699, \"to\": 3704}, {\"ngram\": \"the enlightenment\", \"from\": 3708, \"to\": 3725}, {\"ngram\": \"liminal spaces\", \"from\": 3762, \"to\": 3776}, {\"ngram\": \"the places\", \"from\": 3793, \"to\": 3803}, {\"ngram\": \"the margins\", \"from\": 3807, \"to\": 3818}, {\"ngram\": \"society\", \"from\": 3822, \"to\": 3829}, {\"ngram\": \"nature\", \"from\": 3851, \"to\": 3857}]}, {\"sentence\": \"With a mortal, virgin mother and a divine father (does that sound familiar?\", \"from\": 3860, \"to\": 3935, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"a mortal, virgin mother\", \"from\": 3865, \"to\": 3888}, {\"ngram\": \"a divine father\", \"from\": 3893, \"to\": 3908}]}, {\"sentence\": \"), Dionysus was ripped from his mother's womb prematurely and so finished the gestational process sewn into his father Zeus's thigh.\", \"from\": 3935, \"to\": 4067, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3938, \"end\": 3946, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}, {\"begin\": 4054, \"end\": 4058, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zeus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 7.784210346557105e-60, \"text\": \"Zeus\", \"types\": [\"Q24229398\", \"Q178885\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zeus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zeus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"his mother's womb\", \"from\": 3963, \"to\": 3980}, {\"ngram\": \"the gestational process\", \"from\": 4009, \"to\": 4032}]}, {\"sentence\": \"He was then raised in Asia, and when he returned to Greece, his divinity was not immediately recognised.\", \"from\": 4068, \"to\": 4172, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4120, \"end\": 4126, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.769617361335612e-20, \"text\": \"Greece\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Asia\", \"from\": 4090, \"to\": 4094}, {\"ngram\": \"his divinity\", \"from\": 4128, \"to\": 4140}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In Euripides' play The Bacchae (405 BC), Pentheus, the Theban King, rejected Dionysus, while the relatively powerless old men and women of the city fled to the country.\", \"from\": 4174, \"to\": 4342, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4210, \"end\": 4212, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Common_Era\", \"score\": 0.9999945553970946, \"rank\": 5.444632433130507e-06, \"text\": \"BC\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Common_Era\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Common_Era\"}, {\"begin\": 4215, \"end\": 4223, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pentheus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Pentheus\", \"types\": [\"Q24229398\", \"Q178885\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pentheus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pentheus\"}, {\"begin\": 4229, \"end\": 4235, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Luxor\", \"score\": 0.999999832496101, \"rank\": 1.6750394399307238e-07, \"text\": \"Theban\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Luxor\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Luxor\"}, {\"begin\": 4236, \"end\": 4240, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Monarch\", \"score\": 0.979274092485128, \"rank\": 0.021164562272589862, \"text\": \"King\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Monarch\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Monarch\"}, {\"begin\": 4251, \"end\": 4259, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Euripides\", \"from\": 4177, \"to\": 4186}, {\"ngram\": \"The Bacchae\", \"from\": 4193, \"to\": 4204}, {\"ngram\": \"the relatively powerless old men\", \"from\": 4267, \"to\": 4299}, {\"ngram\": \"women\", \"from\": 4304, \"to\": 4309}, {\"ngram\": \"the city\", \"from\": 4313, \"to\": 4321}, {\"ngram\": \"the country\", \"from\": 4330, \"to\": 4341}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Later, he became known as the deity whoguides reincarnation and promises immortality.\", \"from\": 4343, \"to\": 4428, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the deity\", \"from\": 4369, \"to\": 4378}, {\"ngram\": \"reincarnation\", \"from\": 4389, \"to\": 4402}, {\"ngram\": \"immortality\", \"from\": 4416, \"to\": 4427}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In this context, the feasting of Dionysus can be understood as not just about unrestrained pleasure, but aboutconnection and the breaking of boundaries.\", \"from\": 4429, \"to\": 4581, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4462, \"end\": 4470, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"this context\", \"from\": 4432, \"to\": 4444}, {\"ngram\": \"the feasting\", \"from\": 4446, \"to\": 4458}, {\"ngram\": \"unrestrained pleasure\", \"from\": 4507, \"to\": 4528}, {\"ngram\": \"aboutconnection\", \"from\": 4534, \"to\": 4549}, {\"ngram\": \"the breaking\", \"from\": 4554, \"to\": 4566}, {\"ngram\": \"boundaries\", \"from\": 4570, \"to\": 4580}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The cults and churches of both Dionysus and Jesus encouraged their practitioners to find meaning in the spaces between: life and death, the power and the might, the human and the divine.\", \"from\": 4583, \"to\": 4769, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4614, \"end\": 4622, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}, {\"begin\": 4627, \"end\": 4632, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\", \"score\": 0.9999999976243998, \"rank\": 2.3757717043300036e-09, \"text\": \"Jesus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The cults\", \"from\": 4583, \"to\": 4592}, {\"ngram\": \"churches\", \"from\": 4597, \"to\": 4605}, {\"ngram\": \"their practitioners\", \"from\": 4644, \"to\": 4663}, {\"ngram\": \"meaning\", \"from\": 4672, \"to\": 4679}, {\"ngram\": \"the spaces\", \"from\": 4683, \"to\": 4693}, {\"ngram\": \"life\", \"from\": 4703, \"to\": 4707}, {\"ngram\": \"death\", \"from\": 4712, \"to\": 4717}, {\"ngram\": \"the power\", \"from\": 4719, \"to\": 4728}, {\"ngram\": \"the might\", \"from\": 4733, \"to\": 4742}, {\"ngram\": \"the human\", \"from\": 4744, \"to\": 4753}, {\"ngram\": \"the divine\", \"from\": 4758, \"to\": 4768}]}, {\"sentence\": \"They also encouraged worship of a god who feasts with all people indiscriminately, in a culture in which eating with people was apowerful sign of relationships.\", \"from\": 4770, \"to\": 4930, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"worship\", \"from\": 4791, \"to\": 4798}, {\"ngram\": \"a god\", \"from\": 4802, \"to\": 4807}, {\"ngram\": \"all people\", \"from\": 4824, \"to\": 4834}, {\"ngram\": \"a culture\", \"from\": 4856, \"to\": 4865}, {\"ngram\": \"people\", \"from\": 4887, \"to\": 4893}, {\"ngram\": \"apowerful sign\", \"from\": 4898, \"to\": 4912}, {\"ngram\": \"relationships\", \"from\": 4916, \"to\": 4929}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The Eucharist feast of early Christianity (which today is \\\"communion\\\" in most modern Christian practices), after all, had similar connotations to the Dionysaic feast.\", \"from\": 4932, \"to\": 5098, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4936, \"end\": 4945, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sacrifice\", \"score\": 0.9989262670191459, \"rank\": 0.001074887122503251, \"text\": \"Eucharist\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sacrifice\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sacrifice\"}, {\"begin\": 4955, \"end\": 4973, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 5.606827794088226e-16, \"text\": \"early Christianity\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/History_of_Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 5017, \"end\": 5026, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999999977158041, \"rank\": 2.2840807942604358e-09, \"text\": \"Christian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"\\\"communion\", \"from\": 4990, \"to\": 5000}, {\"ngram\": \"similar connotations\", \"from\": 5054, \"to\": 5074}, {\"ngram\": \"the Dionysaic feast\", \"from\": 5078, \"to\": 5097}]}, {\"sentence\": \"They can both be interpreted as symbols of broken social boundaries, as well as the broken boundary between the human and the divine.\", \"from\": 5099, \"to\": 5232, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"symbols\", \"from\": 5131, \"to\": 5138}, {\"ngram\": \"broken social boundaries\", \"from\": 5142, \"to\": 5166}, {\"ngram\": \"the broken boundary\", \"from\": 5179, \"to\": 5198}, {\"ngram\": \"the human\", \"from\": 5207, \"to\": 5216}, {\"ngram\": \"the divine\", \"from\": 5221, \"to\": 5231}]}, {\"sentence\": \"These sentiments have largely been lost after centuries of Christian hegemony, during which participation in the Eucharist has been used as a political weapon and as a way of establishing and publicly enforcing societal norms.\", \"from\": 5233, \"to\": 5459, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5292, \"end\": 5301, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999999977158041, \"rank\": 2.2840807942604358e-09, \"text\": \"Christian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 5346, \"end\": 5355, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sacrifice\", \"score\": 0.9989262670191459, \"rank\": 0.001074887122503251, \"text\": \"Eucharist\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sacrifice\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sacrifice\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"These sentiments\", \"from\": 5233, \"to\": 5249}, {\"ngram\": \"centuries\", \"from\": 5279, \"to\": 5288}, {\"ngram\": \"which participation\", \"from\": 5319, \"to\": 5338}, {\"ngram\": \"a political weapon\", \"from\": 5373, \"to\": 5391}, {\"ngram\": \"a way\", \"from\": 5399, \"to\": 5404}, {\"ngram\": \"societal norms\", \"from\": 5444, \"to\": 5458}]}, {\"sentence\": \"It is undoubtedly true that the connections between Dionysus and Christ exist in the context of a larger blending of pre-Christian and Christian Mediterranean culture.\", \"from\": 5461, \"to\": 5628, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5513, \"end\": 5521, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}, {\"begin\": 5596, \"end\": 5605, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999999977158041, \"rank\": 2.2840807942604358e-09, \"text\": \"Christian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the connections\", \"from\": 5489, \"to\": 5504}, {\"ngram\": \"Christ\", \"from\": 5526, \"to\": 5532}, {\"ngram\": \"the context\", \"from\": 5542, \"to\": 5553}, {\"ngram\": \"a larger blending\", \"from\": 5557, \"to\": 5574}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But focusing on the specific connections between Dionysus and Christ seems particularly relevant in this situation.\", \"from\": 5629, \"to\": 5744, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5678, \"end\": 5686, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the specific connections\", \"from\": 5645, \"to\": 5669}, {\"ngram\": \"Christ\", \"from\": 5691, \"to\": 5697}, {\"ngram\": \"this situation\", \"from\": 5729, \"to\": 5743}]}, {\"sentence\": \"There is, after all, a certain irony that a type of ceremonial feasting, associated with reaching out to the marginalised and breaking boundaries, is being weaponised to reinforce boundaries and further marginalise the marginalised.\", \"from\": 5745, \"to\": 5977, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"a certain irony\", \"from\": 5766, \"to\": 5781}, {\"ngram\": \"a type\", \"from\": 5787, \"to\": 5793}, {\"ngram\": \"ceremonial feasting\", \"from\": 5797, \"to\": 5816}, {\"ngram\": \"the marginalised and breaking boundaries\", \"from\": 5850, \"to\": 5890}, {\"ngram\": \"boundaries\", \"from\": 5925, \"to\": 5935}, {\"ngram\": \"the marginalised\", \"from\": 5960, \"to\": 5976}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The response to the tableau at the Paris Olympics opening ceremony highlights the overlooked historical connections between Christian and Greco-Roman religious imagery.\", \"from\": 5979, \"to\": 6147, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6103, \"end\": 6112, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"score\": 0.9999999977158041, \"rank\": 2.2840807942604358e-09, \"text\": \"Christian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Christianity\"}, {\"begin\": 6117, \"end\": 6128, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"score\": 0.9999999883048077, \"rank\": 1.169455312396202e-08, \"text\": \"Greco-Roman\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Greek_mythology\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The response\", \"from\": 5979, \"to\": 5991}, {\"ngram\": \"the tableau\", \"from\": 5995, \"to\": 6006}, {\"ngram\": \"the Paris Olympics opening ceremony\", \"from\": 6010, \"to\": 6045}, {\"ngram\": \"the overlooked historical connections\", \"from\": 6057, \"to\": 6094}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But it also provides an opportunity to recognise the profound connections many historians see between Dionysus and Jesus.\", \"from\": 6148, \"to\": 6269, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6250, \"end\": 6258, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.994664468897347e-48, \"text\": \"Dionysus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus\"}, {\"begin\": 6263, \"end\": 6268, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\", \"score\": 0.9999999976243998, \"rank\": 2.3757717043300036e-09, \"text\": \"Jesus\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Jesus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"an opportunity\", \"from\": 6169, \"to\": 6183}, {\"ngram\": \"the profound connections\", \"from\": 6197, \"to\": 6221}, {\"ngram\": \"many historians\", \"from\": 6222, \"to\": 6237}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Particularly their shared themes of divine suffering, resurrection, and boundary breaking.\", \"from\": 6270, \"to\": 6360, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Particularly their shared themes\", \"from\": 6270, \"to\": 6302}, {\"ngram\": \"divine suffering\", \"from\": 6306, \"to\": 6322}, {\"ngram\": \"resurrection\", \"from\": 6324, \"to\": 6336}, {\"ngram\": \"boundary breakin